AIM

To demonstrate tuple operations in Python such as accessing elements, finding length, counting elements, finding index, maximum and minimum values, sorting, reversing and looping through tuple elements.

Algorithm

Start the program.
Create two tuples named students and marks.
Access and display the first and second elements of the students tuple.
Find the length of the tuple using len().
Count the occurrence of a value in the tuple.
Find the index of a specific element.
Display the maximum and minimum values from the marks tuple.
Sort the marks tuple and display it.
Reverse the marks tuple.
Traverse the students tuple using a loop and display each element.
Stop the program.

SOURCE CODE

students = ("Roy", 21, "Arpit", "Ram")
marks = (21, 54, 95, 56, 67)

print("First element:", students[0])
print("Second element:", students[1])

print("Length of tuple:", len(students))

print("Count of Roy:", students.count("Roy"))

print("Index of 21:", students.index(21))

print("The max element:", max(marks))

print("The min element:", min(marks))

print("Sorted tuple:", sorted(marks))

print("Reversed:", list(reversed(marks)))

print("Looping through tuple:")
for item in students:
    print(item)

